    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "Reflexive verbs pair with reflexive pronouns: me, te, se, nos, os, se. The pronoun always matches the subject—'me' for I, 'te' for you, 'se' for he/she/they. It usually sits before the conjugated verb: 'Me levanto' (I get up). When the verb is an infinitive, gerund, or command, the pronoun attaches to the end: 'levantarse,' 'levantándote,' 'levántate.'"
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Reflexive verbs grew from Latin phrases that joined actions with 'se,' meaning self.",
