{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_A2_013_future_with_ir_a",
  "title": "A2.13 Future with “Ir a” — Talking About What’s Coming",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we form the near future with will or going to: I will study, I am going to study. Spanish uses the same pattern as the second one—'ir a' plus an infinitive. English hints at intention with helpers; Spanish turns the idea of movement into the grammar of plans."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "Conjugate ir (voy, vas, va, vamos, vais, van), add a, then the infinitive verb: 'Voy a estudiar' (I’m going to study). The subject decides the form of ir, not the main verb. Negative forms place no before ir: 'No voy a salir.' This structure expresses planned, certain, or immediate future events—the grammar of intention rather than prophecy."
