{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_A2_025_pronouns_with_commands",
  "title": "A2.25 Pronouns with Commands — Giving and Asking at the Same Time",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we keep pronouns in place when giving commands: Tell me, Don’t touch it. Spanish shifts them depending on whether the command is positive or negative. English stays steady; Spanish choreographs movement. English speaks flat; Spanish turns giving instructions into a small dance of placement."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "In affirmative commands, attach pronouns to the end: 'Dímelo' (Tell it to me). In negative commands, place them before the verb: 'No me lo digas' (Don’t tell it to me). Accent marks often appear on the stressed syllable to keep pronunciation natural. The order always stays indirect pronoun first, then direct: 'me lo,' 'te la,' 'se los.'"
    },
    {
