{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_A2_037_sequence_of_tenses",
  "title": "A2.37 The Sequence of Tenses — Keeping Verbs in Harmony",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, tense relationships feel natural: I think she knows, I thought she knew. Spanish follows the same logic but applies it more strictly. English adjusts by instinct; Spanish by rule. English lets tenses drift; Spanish keeps them in rhythm so the time of one verb matches the other."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "If the main clause is in the present, the subordinate clause uses the present or present subjunctive: 'Creo que viene.' If the main clause is in the past, the subordinate shifts to the past or imperfect subjunctive: 'Creía que venía.' Present calls present; past calls past. The rule maintains harmony of time and perspective across verbs."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "This principle comes from Latin grammar, where time consistency between clauses was mandatory for clarity and flow.",
      "story": "Latin linked verb forms like notes in a melody—each tense aligning with its lead. Spanish inherited that discipline, turning storytelling into choreography. The rule doesn’t limit expression; it synchronizes it. Sequence of tenses ensures that emotion and time breathe together, that every cause, hope, or doubt stays in its rightful moment.",
